    <summary>Pieter Wuille, a Bitcoin Core developer, has proposed a softfork to make non-DER signatures illegal due to recent events that have made clear the risks of depending on OpenSSL for consensus rules. The proposal involves replacing the dependency on OpenSSL with the libsecp256k1 library, which will provide signature verification and public key recovery functionality. The draft BIP text and implementation can be found on GitHub, and comments and criticisms are welcome.Furthermore, Pieter Wuille proposed an improvement to the Bitcoin protocol that would replace OpenSSL with libsecp256k1. The proposal was made in light of recent events that revealed the risks of depending on OpenSSL for consensus rules.In January of 2015, Pieter Wuille proposed a softfork to make non-DER signatures illegal in order to fix the issue of transaction malleability and reduce the risk of depending on OpenSSL for consensus rules. The proposal was assigned the BIP number 0066 and received positive feedback from several implementers. However, there were concerns raised about the possibility of an nlocked spend with an invalidly encoded signature.In February of that same year, Wuille proposed a one-line change to BIP66's DERSIG that would softfork but later retracted it after it was pointed out that there were still edge-cases that weren't covered. Instead, a cleaner solution was proposed: only allow an empty byte vector as an invalid signature. Pieter also suggested individual R and S length restrictions that would limit them to no more than 32 bytes, excluding the padding 0 byte in front, to standardness requirements.The proposed changes were shared on the Bitcoin Development mailing list along with sample codes and test cases to ensure compatibility. These codes include various valid and invalid byte sequences that are used to test the validity of signatures in a Bitcoin transaction. Lastly, Pieter Wuille has proposed replacing OpenSSL with libsecp256k1, which will provide signature verification and public key recovery functionality, which are currently handled by OpenSSL. The proposed changes aim to address the risks of depending on OpenSSL for consensus rules and provide a more fundamental solution to the problem.In various email exchanges and proposals discussed in this context, Bitcoin Core developer Pieter Wuille proposed a softfork to make non-DER signatures illegal due to the risk of depending on OpenSSL for consensus rules. A draft BIP text and implementation with unit tests can be found on GitHub, and comments and criticisms are welcome.In addition, Pieter suggested an upper bound for R/S length in IsStandard and STRICTDER, which was agreed upon by Gregory Maxwell. There were also proposals to modify BIP66's DERSIG to address non-standard transactions, and Pieter suggested a simpler alternative that would softfork with only a one-line change. However, it was later retracted after edge-cases were discovered. In another email exchange, Gavin Andresen recommended nit-picky changes to DERSIG BIP and provided feedback on updating the "DER standard." Lastly, Pieter received feedback from Douglas Roark regarding his paper and code for handling invalid signatures in Bitcoin transactions.Zooko's review of the links provided by the author and suggestions for improvements to the code. Zooko recommends verifying all branches of the new IsDERSignature() function and finishing the TODOs so that it tests the upgrade behavior. He also suggests including a rationale or link to accept the 0-length sig as correctly-encoded-but-invalid in the bipstrictder proposal.There is also a discussion about making non-standard transactions invalid and two solutions are presented: adding a patch to version 0.10 or modifying BIP66's DERSIG with a simple one-line change. Despite concerns about it being too late for version 0.10, there is no opposition to implementing the proposed solution.Lastly, the context mentioned various implementations of BIP0066 available on Gi